[h3 id=RecordingAVideo 
	" Recording a Video
	$LF
]h3
[h4 id=HowDoIMakeItStopSplittingTheVideoNear2gb 
	" How do I make it stop splitting the video near 2GB?
	$LF
]h4
[ul 
	[li 
		" 
		[em 
			"File -> AVI/WAV -> Config and Record AVI/WAV -> FFmpeg writer -> AVI Lossless FFV1
		]em
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[h4 id=HowToPreventSplittingOnResolutionChanges 
	" How to prevent splitting on resolution changes?
	$LF
]h4
[ul 
	[li 
		" 
		[em 
			"File -> AVI/WAV -> Config and Record AVI/WAV -> Resize Video
		]em
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[div class=p 
	"The resizing filter is Nearest Neighbor.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Another option (allows to control resizing filter):
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" Set exact window resolution:
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" 
				[em 
					"Config -> Display -> Use custom size
				]em
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
	]li
	[li 
		" Set 
		[code 
			"Final Filter
		]code
		" for resizing.
		$LF
	]li
	[li 
		" Make Bizhawk capture client area instead of the internal framebuffer:
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" 
				[em 
					"File -> AVI/WAV -> Capture OSD
				]em
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
	]li
	[li 
		" Disable on-scree-display itself if you want:
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" 
				[em 
					"View -> Display blah-blah
				]em
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
	]li
]ul
[h4 id=RecordedVideoHasTinyResolutionHowToFixThat 
	" The recorded video has tiny resolution. How to fix that?
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"Do the same as right above, just set some real high resolution. In this case you won't need lossless video, so pick something lighter:
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		" 
		[em 
			"File -> AVI/WAV -> Config and Record AVI/WAV -> FFmpeg writer -> Matroska
		]em
		$LF
	]li
]ul
[h4 id=AviWriterCrashesWhenITryToSelectACodecOrEvenCancel 
	" AVI Writer crashes when I try to select a codec or even cancel
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"In 
	[code 
		"regedit
	]code
	", go to 
	[code 
		"HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Drivers32
	]code
	" and look for all names that start with 
	[code 
		"VIDC
	]code
	" (any case). One of them is probably your issue.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=Tastudio 
	" TAStudio
	$LF
]h3
[h4 id=MyTastudioProjectGotCorruptedAndDoesnTLoadAnymoreWhatDoIDo 
	" My TAStudio project got corrupted and doesn't load anymore. What do I do?
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"TAStudio projects are 
	[code 
		".zip
	]code
	" files. Get latest 7zip, open your 
	[code 
		".tasproj
	]code
	" with it, and remove the 
	[code 
		"GreenZone
	]code
	" file.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"If it can't remove it, unzip the whole 
	[code 
		".tasproj
	]code
	" to some folder (ignore the errors/warnings), remove the 
	[code 
		"GreenZone
	]code
	" file, compress everything back to 
	[code 
		".zip
	]code
	", and rename that to 
	[code 
		".tasproj
	]code
	".
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"If the 
	[code 
		".tasproj
	]code
	" still has issues loading, you can create a new 
	[code 
		".tasproj
	]code
	" using BizHawk, unzip it to a new folder, copy the previous 
	[code 
		"Input Log.txt
	]code
	" file over, and recompress that movie.
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=TastudioForcesAnEmptyFrameAtTheEndOfMyInputsHowDoIRemoveIt 
	" TAStudio forces an empty frame at the end of my inputs. How do I remove it?
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"It's not an extra frame, it's just a visual representation of when your last input will be sent to the game. See how TAStudio's first frame is 0? That is the point before anything has been emulated, it's just a way to send inputs to the game on its 
	[b 
		"first
	]b
	" frame of emulation, which is listed as frame 1 in TAStudio.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"During old-school movie recording (without TAStudio) you hold down your inputs before the frame you need, and hit the Frame Advance hotkey, and that way those inputs are being recorded to your movie file. If you open that movie as an archive and then open 
	[code 
		"Input Log.txt
	]code
	" in a text editor, you won't see the 0th frame there when you started holding down your inputs, you'll only see the 1st frame when you've actually sent them to the game. Similarly if you open your 
	[code 
		".tasproj
	]code
	" file the same way, the last "empty" frame won't be there. Because the last frame is when the game has 
	[b 
		"received
	]b
	" your last inputs.
]div
